{{Infobox supercluster | name = Hercules [[Superclusters]] | image = Nearsc.gif | image_size = 300px | caption = Hercules Superclusters are shown at the top right | credit = | epoch = | constellation = [[Hercules (constellation)|Hercules]] | ra = <!-- {{RA|00|00}} --> | dec = <!-- {{DEC|±00|00}} --> | brightest_member = | member_no = | major_axis_mpc = {{convert|100|Mpc|Mly|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} | minor_axis_mpc = <!-- {{convert|000|Mpc|Mly|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} {{hub|0.00}} --> | redshift = 0.0304-0.0414<ref name=kopylova/> | distance = <!-- {{convert|000|Mpc|Mly|0|abbr=on|lk=on}} {{hub|0.00}} --> | mass = <!-- 0{{e|14}} {{hub|0.00}} [[solar mass|M<sub>☉</sub>]] --> | luminosity = | flux = | other_names = SCl 160 }} The '''Hercules Superclusters''' ('''SCl 160''') refers to a set of two nearby [[supercluster]]s of [[galaxies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlasoftheuniverse.com/superc/her.html |title=The Hercules Superclusters |publisher=Atlasoftheuniverse.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-19}}</ref>
Relative to other local superclusters, Hercules is considered particularly large, being approximately 330 Mly in diameter. The [[Northern Local Supervoid]] lies in front of the superclusters, and is as big as the superclusters themselves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://physics.gmu.edu/~jevans/astr103/CourseNotes/ECText/ch22_txt.htm#22.4.3 |title=Astronomy Supplement - A Universe of Galaxies |publisher=Physics.gmu.edu |date=1999-03-09 |accessdate=2011-11-19}}</ref> The redshifts of the member galaxies lie between 0.0304 and 0.0414.<ref name=kopylova>{{cite journal|author1=Kopylova, F. G. |author2=Kopylov, A. I. |date=2013|title=Investigation of properties of galaxy clusters in the Hercules supercluster region|journal=Astronomy Letters|volume=39|issue=1|pages=1–16|doi=10.1134/S1063773712120043 | bibcode= 2013AstL...39....1K }}</ref>
The region includes [[Abell 2147]], [[Hercules Cluster|Abell 2151]] (Hercules Cluster), and [[Abell 2152]] [[galaxy clusters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tdc-www.harvard.edu/instruments/fast/progs/48/ |title=Program 48: Hercules Supercluster |publisher=Tdc-www.harvard.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-11-19}}</ref><ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|url=https://netfiles.uiuc.edu/lthomps/www/webpage-2010/void.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120630223528/https://netfiles.uiuc.edu/lthomps/www/webpage-2010/void.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2012-06-30 |title=Voids and Superclusters |publisher=Netfiles.uiuc.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-11-19 }}</ref> An extremely long filament of galaxies has been found, that connects this group of clusters to the [[Abell 2197]] and [[Abell 2199]] pair.<ref name="autogenerated1"/> [[Abell 2162]] in the nearby constellation [[Corona Borealis]] is also a member.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Einasto, M. |author2=Einasto, J. |author3=Tago, E. |author4=Müller, V. |author5=Andernach, H. |date=2001|title=Optical and X-Ray Clusters as Tracers of the Supercluster-Void Network. I. Superclusters of Abell and X-Ray Clusters|journal=The Astronomical Journal|volume=122|issue=5|pages=2222–2242| doi=10.1086/323707 |bibcode=2001AJ....122.2222E|arxiv = astro-ph/0012536 }}</ref>
The Hercules Superclusters are near the [[Coma Supercluster]], helping make up part of the [[CfA2 Great Wall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ned.ipac.caltech.edu/level5/Sept01/Bahcall2/Bahcall9_2.html |title=Clusters and Superclusters of Galaxies |publisher=Ned.ipac.caltech.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-11-19}}</ref>
