In [[hydrography]], the '''Navigation Surface''' paradigm represents an alternative to traditional approaches to manage [[bathymetry|bathymetric data]] by creating bathymetric databases that can be used to generate high-resolution navigation aids and other applications.<ref name="auto">{{cite thesis|type=Masters|title=The Navigation Surface: A Multipurpose Bathymetric Database|last1=Smith|first1=Shepard|date=2003|publisher=[[University of New Hampshire]] |url=http://ccom.unh.edu/publications/navigation-surface-multipurpose-bathymetric-database |location=Durham, NH|pages=|accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref> 

The paradigm also provides methods to manipulate the data to create products for various applications (e.g., [[thematic map]]s for [[marine geology]],[[acoustic seabed classification]] and [[marine biology]]).{{citation needed|date= June 2018}}

== History ==

Recent technological developments in [[hydrography]] (e.g., large adoption of [[multibeam echosounder]] and [[electronic navigational chart]]s) have pushed [[hydrographic office|hydrographic organizations]] to adopt a new production paradigm centered on gridded surfaces rather than sounding-based workflow and products.<ref name="titley">{{cite journal |last1=Titley |first1=David |title=Implementation of Navigation Surface |journal=Hydro International |date=26 June 2009 |url=https://www.hydro-international.com/content/article/implementation-of-navigation-surface |accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>

Based on such a shift, the concept of navigation surface was introduced in 2003 to provide a [[seafloor]] model at the best resolution that the data support. Depth values for nautical charting are then derived by [[cartographic generalization|generalization]] of the available gridded surfaces. In addition, a quality assessment for each grid node of the navigation surface is created through an uncertainty layer.<ref name="auto"/>

The Open Navigation Surface (ONS) project designed a free, [[open-source software|open-source code]] library to manage (read/write) the information required to create a Navigation Surface. The implementation of these requirements is represented by the [[Bathymetric Attributed Grid]] data format.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Open Navigation Surface project |url=http://www.opennavsurf.org/index.html |accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref>

The [[US Navy]] has implemented a global navigation surface [[database]] using an infrastructure called DBDB-NV.<ref name="titley"/>

